Step 1.5 - Create Tampa_crimemape

Create an object called Tampa_crimemap based on simpleMap, where each point represents one crime.

It should look like this:

Step 1.5 Map

# Write your code below.
library(janitor)
## 
## Attaching package: 'janitor'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     chisq.test, fisher.test
# To prevent the graph from looking too busy, we will only select the data that includes frequently occuring Description.
# Use tabyl to create a table that shows how many each descriptions are.
description <- tabyl(PoliceCall, Description)
# Using the median number of each description count, create a list of description that showed up on the data for more than the median number of times.
filter_desc <- description[description$n > median(description$n),]


# Create a new dataset that includes only the elements included in the list we created above.
PoliceCall_filtered <- subset(PoliceCall, Description %in% filter_desc$Description)

Tampa_crimemap <- simpleMap + geom_point(data = PoliceCall_filtered, aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, color = Description)) + guides(col = guide_legend(ncol = 1)) + theme(legend.key.size = unit(10, "point"))

Tampa_crimemap
